  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Oakland Edges Chicago Cubs In Ten-Inning Thriller",
    "subheadline": "ATH 5, CHC 4 in a marathon that went to the 10th.",
    "lead_angle": "Under the gloaming lights of Wrigley Field, the Oakland Athletics wrestled away a critical victory from the Chicago Cubs, pushing across a single run in the tenth inning to secure a hard-fought 5-4 win. The decisive blow came against Cubs reliever Ethan Roberts, who conceded the go-ahead score, leaving the home faithful silent as Hogan Harris claimed the victory for Oakland, and Justin Sterner closed out the final three outs for the save.\n\nThe contest began as a display of power, with Colby Thomas putting the Athletics ahead briefly with a solo shot in the first, only for Chicago to answer with a Pete Crow-Armstrong two-run blast in the third, followed by Seiya Suzuki's solo homer in the fourth. The Cubs held a comfortable 4-1 lead entering the eighth, but the Oakland lineup, long dormant, finally stirred. Two runs in the top of the eighth inning against the Chicago bullpen erased the deficit, knotting the score and forcing extra frames, fundamentally shifting the game's energy.\n\nAt the heart of Oakland’s late surge was Tyler Soderstrom, whose two hits and two crucial runs batted in powered the comeback that revitalized the Athletics. His efforts underscore a growing maturity at the plate, vital for an Oakland club fighting to stay relevant in a tightly contested American League race. This victory, a grinding affair at the venerable ballpark, kept the Athletics clinging to faint playoff hopes, a testament to resilience on a day they could have folded.",
    "reason": "Marathon ball. 10 innings of sustained tension makes this the day's standout."
  },
